## Part 3 – Security and best practices (OWASP SPVS aligned)

- **Secrets:** AWS Secrets Manager / ESO / External Secrets Operator; never commit. No hardcoded API tokens or secrets.
- **Scanning:** tfsec/checkov, trivy, kube-bench in CI.
- **Multi-account:** AWS Organizations, SCPs, landing zones.
- **Content:** Markdown/tutorials with code blocks and Mermaid diagrams.

### 3.1 OWASP SPVS (Secure Pipeline Verification Standard)

Align pipeline security with **OWASP SPVS** when working on compliance workflows, dependency scanning, or release assurance.

- **What:** Framework to assess and improve security maturity of **software delivery pipelines** (not only application code).
- **Version:** 1.0 (October 2025).
- **Lifecycle:** **Plan, Develop, Integrate, Release, Operate**.
- **Model:** Multi-tiered maturity; can align with CIS, OWASP ASVS, cloud Well-Architected.
- **Scope:** Artifact integrity, build environment protection, release assurance, automated validation.
- **References:** [OWASP SPVS project](https://owasp.org/www-project-spvs), GitHub: `OWASP/www-project-spvs`.

**Relation to common tooling:**

- **OWASP Dependency-Check** (image/action) maps to SPVS **Develop** and **Integrate** (dependency/SCA). Use current versions; map controls to SPVS as needed.
- **Compliance-style workflows** (e.g. Trivy, Buildah, GHCR) support **Integrate** / **Release** (scan, build, push) and **Operate** (visibility).

When adding or changing pipeline security, note which SPVS stage(s) are covered and document or reference SPVS where useful.

### 3.2 DevSecOps security standards (non-negotiable)

- **Shell in GitHub Actions:** Never use `${{ github.event... }}` directly inside a `run:` block. Map untrusted context to `env:` variables, then use `"$VAR"` in the script. Always start scripts with `set -euo pipefail`; always double-quote variables to prevent word splitting and globbing.
- **Python:** Never use `shell=True` in subprocess; pass args as a list. Forbid `eval()`, `exec()`, and `os.system()`. Use `shlex.quote()` only if you must build a shell string; prefer list-based subprocess.
- **GitHub Actions hardening:** Every workflow/job must have an explicit `permissions:` block; default to `contents: read`. Pin third-party actions by full SHA (40-char) where required by policy. If generating sensitive values in a step, call `echo "::add-mask::$VALUE"` immediately.
- **Prohibited:** `curl | bash` without checksum verification; hardcoded secrets; workflow-level `permissions: write-all` (or equivalent broad write). Trigger a warning and suggest a fix when these appear.

